TY  - JOUR
T1  - New Knowledge Products As Bricolage: Metaphors and Scripts in Organizational Theory
AU  - Boxenbaum, Eva
AU  - Rouleau, Linda
Y1  - 2011/04/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0213
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2009.0213
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 272
EP  - 296
VL  - 36
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We argue that three epistemic scripts of knowledge production?evolution, differentiation, and bricolage?underpin the production?that is, the conception and the presentation?of new organizational theories. Bricolage of concepts, empirical material, and metaphors enables the conception of new theories, whereas evolution and differentiation, carrying higher academic legitimacy, predominate in theory presentation. We develop an integrative model and provide an illustration from organizational institutionalism to delineate how metaphors and scripts influence organizational theory production.
AB  - We argue that three epistemic scripts of knowledge production?evolution, differentiation, and bricolage?underpin the production?that is, the conception and the presentation?of new organizational theories. Bricolage of concepts, empirical material, and metaphors enables the conception of new theories, whereas evolution and differentiation, carrying higher academic legitimacy, predominate in theory presentation. We develop an integrative model and provide an illustration from organizational institutionalism to delineate how metaphors and scripts influence organizational theory production.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0213
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2009.0213
Y2  - 2026/04/24
